{"key":"post-12594585","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12594585</id>\n<content>One can boil in the soak water or change it for fresh, either one.&amp;nbsp; When I lived in the city, I'd always boil in the soak water for the sake of expediency.&amp;nbsp; However, now that I live in the mountains and have a septic tank, I like to pour the bacteria infested water down the drain because it helps to keep the septic tank working properly.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Burst kernels are from simmering or boiling without properly soaking first.&amp;nbsp; Rinse the grains in hot tap water and begin the soak in hot tap water.&amp;nbsp; After 4 to 24 hours, you can bring them to a rapid boil for ten minutes and then drain.&amp;nbsp; This is how it's shown in the DVD and results in zero burst kernels.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>12594442</prev>\n<first>12593867</first>\n<last>12594585</last>\n<when>1274322679</when>\n<utime>05/20/10 05:31 AM</utime>\n</post>"}